'''PANAMIN''', also Panamin or Panamin Foundation, was the non[[stock]], [[nonprofit]] organization created to protect the interests of [[Philippines|Philippine]] cultural minorities. Headed and mainly funded by [[Manuel Elizalde|Manuel Elizalde, Jr.]], eldest son of a Filipino millionaire, but sometimes funded by the Philippine government under [[President]] [[Ferdinand Marcos]], PANAMIN means Presidential Assistant on National Minorities.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marcos|first1=Ferdinand E|title=PRESIDENTIAL DECREE No. 1414|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/presidentialdecrees/presidentialdecreeno1414.html#.Wh9Ir0pKuM8|publisher=Chan Robles Library|accessdate=29 November 2017|date=June 8, 1978}}</ref> Established in 1968, the organization dissolved in 1983 when Elizalde fled the Philippines.
Notably, [[Charles Lindbergh]] served on PANAMIN's board of directors and visited many of the Philippines' [[indigenous peoples]] with Elizalde.{{CN|date=November 2017}}
